    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-11-18T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-11-18T06:00:00-05:00" n="1248"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1248">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">874.00 TA/11–1853: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 1248<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom (<persName
                            corresp="#p_AWW1" type="from">Aldrich</persName>) to the <gloss
                            type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1248fn1">Repeated to Cairo as telegram 562.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-11-18T11:00:00+00:00"
                            >November 18, 1953—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2135. For the Secretary. At his request I saw <persName corresp="#p_ESA1"
                        >Eden</persName> late yesterday. He handed me following reply to message
                    contained <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 2603, November 13: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I must most urgently ask you to postpone a decision on proposed economic
                            aid to Egypt at least until we have had a chance of discussing it at
                                Bermuda.<note n="2" xml:id="d1248fn2">The Bermuda Conference of the
                                Heads of Government of the United States, United Kingdom, and
                                France, which had been postponed in June 1953, was rescheduled and
                                held Dec. 4–8. Both Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_DJF2"
                                    >Dulles</persName> and Foreign Secretary <persName
                                    corresp="#p_ESA1">Eden</persName> were present for the meetings.
                                Regarding the conference, see telegram 638 to Cairo, Dec. 9, <ref
                                    target="#d1249">
                                    <hi rend="italic">infra</hi>
                                </ref>, and telegram 649 to Cairo, <ref target="#d1250">Document
                                    1250</ref>. For additional documentation, see <ref
                                    target="frus1952-54v05p2#pg_1710">vol. V, Part 2, pp. 1710</ref>
                                ff.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>In my view an allotment to Egypt at this juncture could not fail to give
                            publicity to a major divergence of British and American policies, and
                            thus to have a serious effect on Anglo-American relations. It would have
                            the appearance of encouraging the Egyptians to stand out in their
                            demands against us and it would remove an important inducement to them
                            to reach an agreement with us”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Report on conversation in following telegram.<note n="3" xml:id="d1248fn3">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AWW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Aldrich</hi>
                            </hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
